Task 1: Understanding Network Segmentation with iptables
Subtask 1.1: Examine Current Network Configuration
First, let's examine the current network setup and understand what we're working with.

Check your current network interfaces:
ip addr show
View current routing table:
ip route show
Check existing iptables rules:
sudo iptables -L -v -n
Display current network connections:
netstat -tuln
Subtask 1.2: Create Virtual Network Interfaces
To simulate network segmentation on a single machine, we'll create virtual network interfaces representing different network segments.

Create the first virtual interface for the DMZ segment:
sudo ip link add name dmz0 type dummy
sudo ip addr add 192.168.10.1/24 dev dmz0
sudo ip link set dmz0 up
Create the second virtual interface for the Internal segment:
sudo ip link add name internal0 type dummy
sudo ip addr add 192.168.20.1/24 dev internal0
sudo ip link set internal0 up
Create the third virtual interface for the Management segment:
sudo ip link add name mgmt0 type dummy
sudo ip addr add 192.168.30.1/24 dev mgmt0
sudo ip link set mgmt0 up
Verify the new interfaces:
ip addr show | grep -E "(dmz0|internal0|mgmt0)"
Subtask 1.3: Enable IP Forwarding
Enable IP forwarding to allow traffic routing between segments:

Enable IP forwarding temporarily:
sudo sysctl net.ipv4.ip_forward=1
Make the change permanent:
echo 'net.ipv4.ip_forward=1' | sudo tee -a /etc/sysctl.conf
Verify IP forwarding is enabled:
cat /proc/sys/net/ipv4/ip_forward
Task 2: Implementing Network Segmentation with iptables
Subtask 2.1: Clear Existing Rules and Set Default Policies
Flush all existing iptables rules:
sudo iptables -F
sudo iptables -X
sudo iptables -t nat -F
sudo iptables -t nat -X
Set default policies (we'll start with ACCEPT and then secure):
sudo iptables -P INPUT ACCEPT
sudo iptables -P FORWARD ACCEPT
sudo iptables -P OUTPUT ACCEPT
Subtask 2.2: Create Basic Segmentation Rules
Now we'll create rules to segment network traffic between our virtual network segments.

Create a script to implement basic segmentation rules:
nano ~/network_segmentation.sh
Add the following content to the script:
#!/bin/bash

# Network Segmentation Script
# This script implements basic network segmentation using iptables

echo "Implementing Network Segmentation Rules..."

# Define network segments
DMZ_NET="192.168.10.0/24"
INTERNAL_NET="192.168.20.0/24"
MGMT_NET="192.168.30.0/24"

# Allow loopback traffic
iptables -A INPUT -i lo -j ACCEPT
iptables -A OUTPUT -o lo -j ACCEPT

# Allow established and related connections
iptables -A INPUT -m state --state ESTABLISHED,RELATED -j ACCEPT
iptables -A FORWARD -m state --state ESTABLISHED,RELATED -j ACCEPT

# DMZ Rules - Allow limited access
# Allow HTTP and HTTPS from any source to DMZ
iptables -A FORWARD -d $DMZ_NET -p tcp --dport 80 -j ACCEPT
iptables -A FORWARD -d $DMZ_NET -p tcp --dport 443 -j ACCEPT

# Allow SSH from management network to DMZ
iptables -A FORWARD -s $MGMT_NET -d $DMZ_NET -p tcp --dport 22 -j ACCEPT

# Internal Network Rules
# Allow internal network to access DMZ services
iptables -A FORWARD -s $INTERNAL_NET -d $DMZ_NET -p tcp --dport 80 -j ACCEPT
iptables -A FORWARD -s $INTERNAL_NET -d $DMZ_NET -p tcp --dport 443 -j ACCEPT

# Block direct access from DMZ to Internal network
iptables -A FORWARD -s $DMZ_NET -d $INTERNAL_NET -j DROP

# Management Network Rules
# Allow management network full access to other segments
iptables -A FORWARD -s $MGMT_NET -j ACCEPT

# Block access from other segments to management network
iptables -A FORWARD -d $MGMT_NET ! -s $MGMT_NET -j DROP

# Log dropped packets for monitoring
iptables -A FORWARD -j LOG --log-prefix "DROPPED: " --log-level 4
iptables -A FORWARD -j DROP

echo "Network segmentation rules applied successfully!"
echo "Use 'sudo iptables -L -v -n' to view current rules"
Make the script executable and run it:
chmod +x ~/network_segmentation.sh
sudo ~/network_segmentation.sh
Verify the rules were applied:
sudo iptables -L FORWARD -v -n
